<!-- ───── PageSection hasBodyWrapper ───── -->
<details>
  <summary>📄 PageSection hasBodyWrapper <span class="badge badge-green" style="margin-left:auto">pf-codemods wins</span></summary>
  <div class="detail-body">
    <h4>What changed in PF6</h4>
    <p>In PF6, <code class="inline-code">PageSection</code> now wraps content in a <code class="inline-code">&lt;div&gt;</code> body wrapper by default. To preserve PF5 behavior (no wrapper), add <code class="inline-code">hasBodyWrapper={false}</code>. The official pf-codemods automatically apply this.</p>

    <h4>Before (main)</h4>
    <pre><code><span class="diff-rm">&lt;PageSection className="vm-catalog"&gt;</span></code></pre>

    <h4>After (PF6 correct)</h4>
    <pre><code><span class="diff-add">&lt;PageSection className="vm-catalog" hasBodyWrapper={false}&gt;</span></code></pre>

    <table>
      <tr><th>Metric</th><th>main</th><th>pf-codemods</th><th>semver/goose</th></tr>
      <tr><td>hasBodyWrapper usage count</td><td>11</td><td class="diff-add">85 (+74) ✅</td><td>11 (unchanged ❌)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PageSection count</td><td>84</td><td>84</td><td>66 (reduced — some replaced with Page)</td></tr>
    </table>

    <p><strong>pf-codemods</strong> adds <code class="inline-code">hasBodyWrapper={false}</code> to 74 PageSection instances (and 1 PageBreadcrumb). <strong>semver/goose</strong> takes a different approach — it wraps some PageSections in <code class="inline-code">&lt;Page&gt;</code> wrappers, which is <strong>incorrect</strong>. The <code class="inline-code">&lt;Page&gt;</code> component is a top-level app container, not a section wrapper.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box warn">
      <strong>semver/goose: Incorrect Page wrapping</strong>
      <pre><code><span class="diff-rm">// ❌ This is NOT the correct PF6 migration:</span>
<span class="diff-add">&lt;Page&gt;</span>
  &lt;PageSection&gt;...&lt;/PageSection&gt;
<span class="diff-add">&lt;/Page&gt;</span>

<span class="diff-add">// ✅ The correct PF6 migration is:</span>
&lt;PageSection <span class="diff-add">hasBodyWrapper={false}</span>&gt;...&lt;/PageSection&gt;</code></pre>
      <p style="color:var(--text-muted)">Adding extra <code>&lt;Page&gt;</code> wrappers creates nested Page contexts and breaks the PatternFly layout system. 14 instances found.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</details>

<!-- ───── StackItem/SplitItem CRASH BUG ───── -->
<details open>
  <summary>💥 StackItem/SplitItem <code>component=</code> Crash Bug <span class="badge badge-red" style="margin-left:auto">BLOCKER — semver/goose only</span></summary>
  <div class="detail-body">
    <h4>The Bug</h4>
    <p>The <strong>semver/goose</strong> branch moved StackItem and SplitItem <em>children content</em> into the <code class="inline-code">component</code> prop. This is <strong>fundamentally wrong</strong>.</p>

    <h4>How <code>component</code> actually works (PF6 source code)</h4>
    <pre><code>// @patternfly/react-core/src/layouts/Stack/StackItem.tsx
export const StackItem = ({ component = 'div', children, ...props }) => {
  <strong>const Component = component as any;</strong>  // expects 'div', 'span', 'section'
  return &lt;Component {...props}&gt;{children}&lt;/Component&gt;;
};</code></pre>
    <p>The <code class="inline-code">component</code> prop specifies the <strong>HTML element type</strong> to render (like <code>'div'</code>, <code>'span'</code>). It does NOT accept JSX content.</p>

    <h4>What semver/goose does (WRONG)</h4>
    <pre><code><span class="diff-rm">// Before (correct — content as children):</span>
&lt;StackItem&gt;{error.message}&lt;/StackItem&gt;

<span class="diff-add">// After (CRASH — string passed as element type):</span>
&lt;StackItem component={error.message} /&gt;
// React tries: &lt;Taking snapshot of running VirtualMachine.&gt;...&lt;/&gt;  💥

<span class="diff-rm">// Before (correct — JSX as children):</span>
&lt;StackItem&gt;&lt;AffinityDescriptionText /&gt;&lt;/StackItem&gt;

<span class="diff-add">// After (CRASH — React element passed as component constructor):</span>
&lt;StackItem component={&lt;AffinityDescriptionText /&gt;} /&gt;
// React tries to call a React element as a function  💥</code></pre>

    <h4>Impact</h4>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Count</th><th>Runtime Effect</th></tr>
      <tr><td>StackItem component={&lt;JSX /&gt;}</td><td class="diff-rm">46</td><td>React error: element used as constructor</td></tr>
      <tr><td>StackItem component={string}</td><td class="diff-rm">20</td><td>Invalid HTML element names</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SplitItem component={&lt;JSX /&gt;}</td><td class="diff-rm">15</td><td>React error: element used as constructor</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SplitItem component={string/JSX}</td><td class="diff-rm">4</td><td>Invalid HTML element names or crashes</td></tr>
      <tr><td colspan="3" style="font-weight:700;color:var(--red)">Total: 85 crash sites across 40+ files</td></tr>
    </table>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <strong>This is NOT a PatternFly 6 migration requirement.</strong> The <code>component</code> prop semantics did not change between PF5 and PF6. This bug was introduced by the AI agent's misunderstanding of the prop's purpose. Every page using Stack or Split layouts would crash at runtime.
    </div>
  </div>
</details>

